"{\"project_key\":\"STLSB\",\"feature_name\":\"SPDM Attestation for JKR Platform (NXP LPC55S69 MCU)\",\"epics\":[{\"summary\":\"[SPDM] SPI Flash & Measurement Pipeline\",\"description\":\"## Overview\\nThis epic covers the vertical slice from SPI flash hardware validation through the complete measurement engine that hashes all 7 JKR platform measurement indices. It includes the SPI flash tap validation, flash read driver, boot slot detection, measurement manifest definition, and the measurement engine itself.\\n\\n## Rationale\\nSPDM attestation requires the MCU to independently measure (hash) JKR firmware and configuration regions via a read-only SPI flash hardware tap. This epic delivers the complete measurement pipeline from raw flash access to verified measurement indices.\\n\\n## Scope Items\\n1. Validate SPI flash tap hardware\\n2. Define measurement manifest\\n3. SPI flash read driver (via hardware tap)\\n4. Active/inactive boot slot detection\\n5. Measurement engine (hash each SPI flash region)\\n6. All 7 measurement indices populated & verified\\n\\n## Open Questions\\n- How does the MCU determine the active JKR boot slot? (detection via SPI flash config region or known marker \u2014 needs confirmation)\\n- What is the eFuse key hash measurement source and format?\\n- What is the platform HW version measurement source?\\n- What happens if SPI flash tap read conflicts with JKR ASIC SPI access?\\n\\n## Assumptions\\n- The SPI flash hardware tap provides reliable read-only access without bus contention issues.\\n- The JKR SPI flash layout (UEFI, CPORT, Config, VPD addresses) is stable and will not change without notice.\\n- The Intel CSS header is included in firmware measurement boundaries for stability.\\n- VPD is treated as a mutable measurement because it is writable via PCIe.\\n- SHA-256 is the mandatory measurement hash algorithm; SHA-384 is optional and negotiable.\",\"components\":[\"firmware\"],\"labels\":[\"feature-planning\"],\"stories\":[{\"summary\":\"[FW] Validate SPI flash tap hardware\",\"description\":\"## Overview\\nValidate that the SPI flash hardware tap on the board allows the NXP LPC55S69 MCU to read JKR SPI flash in read-only mode, parallel to JKR's SPI bus. Confirm signal integrity and bus contention behavior.\\n\\n## Rationale\\nThe entire measurement pipeline depends on reliable, read-only SPI flash access via the hardware tap. This validation must be completed before any SPI flash driver or measurement work begins.\\n\\n## Dependencies\\n- None (root item)\\n\\n## Acceptance Criteria\\n- [ ] MCU can read known data patterns from JKR SPI flash via hardware tap\\n- [ ] No bus contention observed when JKR ASIC is also accessing SPI flash\\n- [ ] Read-only access confirmed (no write capability via tap)\\n- [ ] Unit tests pass for relevant functionality\\n- [ ] Code reviewed and merged\\n\\n## Confidence: HIGH\\n## Complexity: S\",\"components\":[\"firmware\"],\"labels\":[\"feature-planning\",\"confidence-high\",\"complexity-s\"],\"complexity\":\"S\",\"confidence\":\"high\",\"acceptance_criteria\":[\"MCU can read known data patterns from JKR SPI flash via hardware tap\",\"No bus contention observed when JKR ASIC is also accessing SPI flash\",\"Read-only access confirmed (no write capability via tap)\",\"Unit tests pass for relevant functionality\",\"Code reviewed and merged\"],\"dependencies\":[],\"assignee\":null},{\"summary\":\"[TOOL] Define measurement manifest\",\"description\":\"## Overview\\nDefine the measurement manifest specifying all 7 measurement indices, their SPI flash boundaries (start address, length), hash algorithm, measurement type (immutable/mutable), and whether Intel CSS headers are included. Document the JKR SPI flash layout mapping.\\n\\n## Rationale\\nThe measurement manifest is the authoritative specification that drives the measurement engine implementation. It must be defined before the measurement engine or measurement index population stories can proceed. It also serves as the contract between firmware and the SPDM Requester for what each measurement index contains.\\n\\n## Dependencies\\n- None (root item)\\n\\n## Acceptance Criteria\\n- [ ] All 7 measurement indices defined with flash address, length, hash algo, and type\\n- [ ] Intel CSS header inclusion policy documented (full image including header)\\n- [ ] VPD marked as mutable type\\n- [ ] eFuse key hash derivation method documented\\n- [ ] Platform HW version encoding documented\\n- [ ] Unit tests pass for relevant functionality\\n- [ ] Code reviewed and merged\\n\\n## Confidence: HIGH\\n## Complexity: M\",\"components\":[\"tools\"],\"labels\":[\"feature-planning\",\"confidence-high\",\"complexity-m\"],\"complexity\":\"M\",\"confidence\":\"high\",\"acceptance_criteria\":[\"All 7 measurement indices defined with flash address, length, hash algo, and type\",\"Intel CSS header inclusion policy documented (full image including header)\",\"VPD marked as mutable type\",\"eFuse key hash derivation method documented\",\"Platform HW version encoding documented\",\"Unit tests pass for relevant functionality\",\"Code reviewed and merged\"],\"dependencies\":[],\"assignee\":null},{\"summary\":\"[FW] SPI flash read driver (via hardware tap)\",\"description\":\"## Overview\\nImplement SPI flash read driver for the MCU to read JKR HFI firmware regions via the hardware SPI tap. Read-only access to known flash layout: UEFI@0x000000, CPORT active@0x220000, CPORT inactive@0x320000, Config@0x2A0000, VPD@0x208000.\\n\\n## Rationale\\nThe measurement engine requires a reliable SPI flash read driver to access JKR firmware and configuration regions. This driver is the data source for all 7 measurement indices.\\n\\n## Dependencies\\n- BLOCKED_BY: Validate SPI flash tap hardware\\n- BLOCKED_BY: MCU project scaffolding (FreeRTOS + NXP SDK + CMake) [in Epic: MCU Platform, Secure Boot & Provisioning]\\n\\n## Acceptance Criteria\\n- [ ] MCU reads known data pattern from each JKR SPI flash region\\n- [ ] Read data matches independent flash dump (via JTAG or external programmer)\\n- [ ] No write operations possible via the hardware tap\\n- [ ] Driver handles SPI flash busy/status correctly\\n- [ ] Unit tests pass for relevant functionality\\n- [ ] Code reviewed and merged\\n\\n## Confidence: MEDIUM\\n## Complexity: M\",\"components\":[\"firmware\"],\"labels\":[\"feature-planning\",\"confidence-medium\",\"complexity-m\"],\"complexity\":\"M\",\"confidence\":\"medium\",\"acceptance_criteria\":[\"MCU reads known data pattern from each JKR SPI flash region\",\"Read data matches independent flash dump (via JTAG or external programmer)\",\"No write operations possible via the hardware tap\",\"Driver handles SPI flash busy/status correctly\",\"Unit tests pass for relevant functionality\",\"Code reviewed and merged\"],\"dependencies\":[\"Validate SPI flash tap hardware\",\"MCU project scaffolding (FreeRTOS + NXP SDK + CMake)\"],\"assignee\":null},{\"summary\":\"[FW] Active/inactive boot slot detection\",\"description\":\"## Overview\\nImplement logic for the MCU to determine which JKR firmware slot (active vs inactive CPORT) is currently booted, so the measurement engine hashes the correct active firmware image. Detection via SPI flash config region or known marker.\\n\\n## Rationale\\nThe JKR platform has dual CPORT firmware slots (active@0x220000, inactive@0x320000). The measurement engine must hash the correct active slot to produce valid attestation measurements. Without boot slot detection, the MCU could measure the wrong firmware image.\\n\\n## Dependencies\\n- BLOCKED_BY: SPI flash read driver (via hardware tap)\\n\\n## Acceptance Criteria\\n- [ ] MCU correctly identifies which CPORT slot is active\\n- [ ] Measurement engine hashes the active slot\\n- [ ] Slot detection works after JKR firmware update (slot swap)\\n- [ ] Detection method documented\\n- [ ] Unit tests pass for relevant functionality\\n- [ ] Code reviewed and merged\\n\\n## Open Question: How does the MCU determine the active JKR boot slot? The detection method (SPI flash config region or known marker) needs to be confirmed with the JKR platform team.\\n\\n## Confidence: MEDIUM\\n## Complexity: M\",\"components\":[\"firmware\"],\"labels\":[\"feature-planning\",\"confidence-medium\",\"complexity-m\"],\"complexity\":\"M\",\"confidence\":\"medium\",\"acceptance_criteria\":[\"MCU correctly identifies which CPORT slot is active\",\"Measurement engine hashes the active slot\",\"Slot detection works after JKR firmware update (slot swap)\",\"Detection method documented\",\"Unit tests pass for relevant functionality\",\"Code reviewed and merged\"],\"dependencies\":[\"SPI flash read driver (via hardware tap)\"],\"assignee\":null},{\"summary\":\"[FW] Measurement engine (hash each SPI flash region)\",\"description\":\"## Overview\\nImplement the measurement engine that hashes each of the 7 measurement indices: MCU FW, JKR CPORT active, JKR UEFI, JKR config, JKR VPD, JKR eFuse key hash, platform HW version. Uses SHA-256 (mandatory) with SHA-384 optional. Full image including Intel CSS header for firmware measurements. VPD marked as mutable type.\\n\\n## Rationale\\nThe measurement engine is the core component that produces the cryptographic hashes served to the SPDM Requester via GET_MEASUREMENTS. It must correctly hash each region per the measurement manifest specification.\\n\\n## Dependencies\\n- BLOCKED_BY: Define measurement manifest\\n- BLOCKED_BY: SPI flash read driver (via hardware tap)\\n\\n## Acceptance Criteria\\n- [ ] All 7 measurement indices produce correct SHA-256 hashes\\n- [ ] Hashes match independent SPI flash dump verification (sha256sum comparison)\\n- [ ] VPD measurement correctly marked as mutable type in SPDM measurement block\\n- [ ] Firmware measurements include Intel CSS header\\n- [ ] SHA-384 hashes produced when negotiated\\n- [ ] Unit tests pass for relevant functionality\\n- [ ] Code reviewed and merged\\n\\n## Confidence: HIGH\\n## Complexity: L\",\"components\":[\"firmware\"],\"labels\":[\"feature-planning\",\"confidence-high\",\"complexity-l\"],\"complexity\":\"L\",\"confidence\":\"high\",\"acceptance_criteria\":[\"All 7 measurement indices produce correct SHA-256 hashes\",\"Hashes match independent SPI flash dump verification (sha256sum comparison)\",\"VPD measurement correctly marked as mutable type in SPDM measurement block\",\"Firmware measurements include Intel CSS header\",\"SHA-384 hashes produced when negotiated\",\"Unit tests pass for relevant functionality\",\"Code reviewed and merged\"],\"dependencies\":[\"Define measurement manifest\",\"SPI flash read driver (via hardware tap)\"],\"assignee\":null},{\"summary\":\"[FW] All 7 measurement indices populated & verified\",\"description\":\"## Overview\\nPopulate and verify all 7 measurement indices with real data from the JKR platform: (1) MCU FW, (2) JKR CPORT active, (3) JKR UEFI, (4) JKR config, (5) JKR VPD, (6) JKR eFuse key hash, (7) platform HW version. Verify each against independent reference.\\n\\n## Rationale\\nThis is the capstone story for the measurement pipeline. All preceding stories (flash driver, boot slot detection, measurement engine, manifest) converge here. The 7 measurement indices must be populated with real platform data and independently verified before the SPDM Responder can serve valid attestation measurements.\\n\\n## Dependencies\\n- BLOCKED_BY: Define measurement manifest\\n- BLOCKED_BY: Measurement engine (hash each SPI flash region)\\n- BLOCKED_BY: Active/inactive boot slot detection\\n\\n## Acceptance Criteria\\n- [ ] All 7 measurement indices return hashes via GET_MEASUREMENTS\\n- [ ] Each hash matches independent verification (sha256sum of flash dump)\\n- [ ] VPD measurement marked as mutable\\n- [ ] eFuse key hash correctly derived\\n- [ ] Platform HW version correctly encoded\\n- [ ] Unit tests pass for relevant functionality\\n- [ ] Code reviewed and merged\\n\\n## Open Questions\\n- What is the eFuse key hash measurement source and format?\\n- What is the platform HW version measurement source?\\n\\n## Confidence: MEDIUM\\n## Complexity: L\",\"components\":[\"firmware\"],\"labels\":[\"feature-planning\",\"confidence-medium\",\"complexity-l\"],\"complexity\":\"L\",\"confidence\":\"medium\",\"acceptance_criteria\":[\"All 7 measurement indices return hashes via GET_MEASUREMENTS\",\"Each hash matches independent verification (sha256sum of flash dump)\",\"VPD measurement marked as mutable\",\"eFuse key hash correctly derived\",\"Platform HW version correctly encoded\",\"Unit tests pass for relevant functionality\",\"Code reviewed and merged\"],\"dependencies\":[\"Define measurement manifest\",\"Measurement engine (hash each SPI flash region)\",\"Active/inactive boot slot detection\"],\"assignee\":null}]},{\"summary\":\"[SPDM] Transport & Protocol Integration\",\"description\":\"## Overview\\nThis epic covers the vertical slice from SMBus hardware validation through the complete SPDM transport stack: I2C/SMBus slave driver, MCTP over SMBus transport layer, libspdm Responder integration, error handling, ResponseNotReady mechanism, and real BMC hardware integration.\\n\\n## Rationale\\nSPDM attestation requires a reliable transport path between the MCU and the BMC. This epic delivers the complete communication stack from physical SMBus through MCTP framing to the SPDM protocol layer, culminating in real hardware integration with the BMC.\\n\\n## Scope Items\\n1. Validate SMBus topology & EID allocation\\n2. I2C/SMBus slave driver for MCTP\\n3. MCTP over SMBus transport layer\\n4. libspdm Responder integration\\n5. ResponseNotReady mechanism for slow CASPER operations\\n6. Error handling & SPDM error responses\\n7. Real SMBus integration (MCU \u2194 BMC on hardware)\\n\\n## Open Questions\\n- What is the BMC's SPDM Requester implementation and version?\\n- The scope item 'Real SMBus integration' depends on 'End-to-end loopback test (spdm_emu over TCP proxy)' which was excluded as a test item. This dependency is noted but the loopback test is not tracked as a separate Story per the no-test-tickets rule. The relevant validation criteria are folded into the Real SMBus integration Story.\\n\\n## Assumptions\\n- Static MCTP EID allocation is sufficient (no dynamic EID assignment needed).\\n- The BMC has a working SPDM 1.2 Requester implementation available for interop testing.\\n- libspdm v3.8.1 is the SPDM library to be used.\",\"components\":[\"firmware\"],\"labels\":[\"feature-planning\"],\"stories\":[{\"summary\":\"[FW] Validate SMBus topology & EID allocation\",\"description\":\"## Overview\\nValidate SMBus/I2C connectivity between MCU and BMC. Allocate a static MCTP Endpoint ID (EID) for the MCU that does not conflict with JKR's existing MCTP EID used for PLDM.\\n\\n## Rationale\\nThe MCTP/SMBus transport stack depends on validated physical connectivity and a conflict-free EID allocation. This must be confirmed before any transport layer development begins.\\n\\n## Dependencies\\n- None (root item)\\n\\n## Acceptance Criteria\\n- [ ] MCU responds to I2C address scan from BMC\\n- [ ] Static EID assigned to MCU does not conflict with JKR ASIC EID\\n- [ ] SMBus communication verified at expected clock rate\\n- [ ] Unit tests pass for relevant functionality\\n- [ ] Code reviewed and merged\\n\\n## Confidence: HIGH\\n## Complexity: S\",\"components\":[\"firmware\"],\"labels\":[\"feature-planning\",\"confidence-high\",\"complexity-s\"],\"complexity\":\"S\",\"confidence\":\"high\",\"acceptance_criteria\":[\"MCU responds to I2C address scan from BMC\",\"Static EID assigned to MCU does not conflict with JKR ASIC EID\",\"SMBus communication verified at expected clock rate\",\"Unit tests pass for relevant functionality\",\"Code reviewed and merged\"],\"dependencies\":[],\"assignee\":null},{\"summary\":\"[FW] I2C/SMBus slave driver for MCTP\",\"description\":\"## Overview\\nImplement I2C slave mode driver on the LPC55S69 for receiving MCTP over SMBus packets from the BMC. MCU acts as an independent MCTP endpoint.\\n\\n## Rationale\\nThe I2C/SMBus slave driver is the lowest layer of the MCTP transport stack. It must correctly handle SMBus block read/write protocol to receive and send MCTP packets from/to the BMC.\\n\\n## Dependencies\\n- BLOCKED_BY: Validate SMBus topology & EID allocation\\n- BLOCKED_BY: MCU project scaffolding (FreeRTOS + NXP SDK + CMake) [in Epic: MCU Platform, Secure Boot & Provisioning]\\n\\n## Acceptance Criteria\\n- [ ] MCU responds to assigned I2C slave address\\n- [ ] I2C loopback test passes\\n- [ ] No blocking in ISR context\\n- [ ] Handles SMBus block read/write protocol correctly\\n- [ ] Unit tests pass for relevant functionality\\n- [ ] Code reviewed and merged\\n\\n## Confidence: MEDIUM\\n## Complexity: M\",\"components\":[\"firmware\"],\"labels\":[\"feature-planning\",\"confidence-medium\",\"complexity-m\"],\"complexity\":\"M\",\"confidence\":\"medium\",\"acceptance_criteria\":[\"MCU responds to assigned I2C slave address\",\"I2C loopback test passes\",\"No blocking in ISR context\",\"Handles SMBus block read/write protocol correctly\",\"Unit tests pass for relevant functionality\",\"Code reviewed and merged\"],\"dependencies\":[\"Validate SMBus topology & EID allocation\",\"MCU project scaffolding (FreeRTOS + NXP SDK + CMake)\"],\"assignee\":null},{\"summary\":\"[FW] MCTP over SMBus transport layer\",\"description\":\"## Overview\\nImplement MCTP over SMBus transport binding per DSP0237. Handle MCTP packet assembly/disassembly, message fragmentation, and the MCTP header for SPDM message type. MCU is a leaf endpoint (no routing/bridging).\\n\\n## Rationale\\nMCTP over SMBus is the transport binding specified by DMTF for SPDM over management buses. This layer sits between the I2C/SMBus slave driver and the SPDM protocol layer, handling packet framing, fragmentation, and message type identification.\\n\\n## Dependencies\\n- BLOCKED_BY: I2C/SMBus slave driver for MCTP\\n\\n## Acceptance Criteria\\n- [ ] MCTP packet encode/decode passes unit tests\\n- [ ] Multi-packet message fragmentation and reassembly works correctly\\n- [ ] MCTP control messages (Get Endpoint ID, Get Message Types) handled\\n- [ ] SPDM message type (0x05) correctly identified in MCTP header\\n- [ ] Unit tests pass for relevant functionality\\n- [ ] Code reviewed and merged\\n\\n## Confidence: HIGH\\n## Complexity: L\",\"components\":[\"firmware\"],\"labels\":[\"feature-planning\",\"confidence-high\",\"complexity-l\"],\"complexity\":\"L\",\"confidence\":\"high\",\"acceptance_criteria\":[\"MCTP packet encode/decode passes unit tests\",\"Multi-packet message fragmentation and reassembly works correctly\",\"MCTP control messages (Get Endpoint ID, Get Message Types) handled\",\"SPDM message type (0x05) correctly identified in MCTP header\",\"Unit tests pass for relevant functionality\",\"Code reviewed and merged\"],\"dependencies\":[\"I2C/SMBus slave driver for MCTP\"],\"assignee\":null},{\"summary\":\"[FW] libspdm Responder integration\",\"description\":\"## Overview\\nIntegrate libspdm v3.8.1 as the SPDM 1.2 Responder. Implement all required callbacks: transport encode/decode, crypto operations, certificate retrieval, measurement retrieval. Configure capabilities: CERT_CAP, CHAL_CAP, MEAS_CAP_SIG. Support full flow: GET_VERSION \u2192 GET_CAPABILITIES \u2192 NEGOTIATE_ALGORITHMS \u2192 GET_DIGESTS \u2192 GET_CERTIFICATE \u2192 CHALLENGE \u2192 GET_MEASUREMENTS.\\n\\n## Rationale\\nThe libspdm Responder integration is the central protocol engine that ties together the transport layer, crypto backend, certificate management, and measurement engine. It is the largest and most critical story in the SPDM feature.\\n\\n## Dependencies\\n- BLOCKED_BY: CASPER crypto backend for Mbed TLS [in Epic: Crypto, Identity & Certificates]\\n- BLOCKED_BY: MCTP over SMBus transport layer\\n\\n## Acceptance Criteria\\n- [ ] libspdm initializes successfully with configured capabilities\\n- [ ] All required callbacks implemented and functional\\n- [ ] SPDM 1.2 version negotiation succeeds\\n- [ ] Algorithm negotiation selects ECC P-256 + SHA-256\\n- [ ] spdm_emu basic SPDM flow passes\\n- [ ] Unit tests pass for relevant functionality\\n- [ ] Code reviewed and merged\\n\\n## Confidence: HIGH\\n## Complexity: XL\",\"components\":[\"firmware\"],\"labels\":[\"feature-planning\",\"confidence-high\",\"complexity-xl\"],\"complexity\":\"XL\",\"confidence\":\"high\",\"acceptance_criteria\":[\"libspdm initializes successfully with configured capabilities\",\"All required callbacks implemented and functional\",\"SPDM 1.2 version negotiation succeeds\",\"Algorithm negotiation selects ECC P-256 + SHA-256\",\"spdm_emu basic SPDM flow passes\",\"Unit tests pass for relevant functionality\",\"Code reviewed and merged\"],\"dependencies\":[\"CASPER crypto backend for Mbed TLS\",\"MCTP over SMBus transport layer\"],\"assignee\":null},{\"summary\":\"[FW] ResponseNotReady mechanism for slow CASPER operations\",\"description\":\"## Overview\\nImplement SPDM ResponseNotReady error response for operations where CASPER crypto latency exceeds SPDM timeout requirements. MCU returns ResponseNotReady with appropriate RDTExponent, and Requester retries with RESPOND_IF_READY.\\n\\n## Rationale\\nThe CASPER crypto accelerator may not complete ECC P-256 sign operations within the SPDM response timeout window. The ResponseNotReady mechanism (per SPDM 1.2 spec) allows the Responder to defer the response and signal the Requester to retry, preventing timeout failures during CHALLENGE and signed GET_MEASUREMENTS.\\n\\n## Dependencies\\n- BLOCKED_BY: Benchmark CASPER crypto on LPC55S69 eval board [in Epic: Crypto, Identity & Certificates]\\n- BLOCKED_BY: libspdm Responder integration\\n\\n## Acceptance Criteria\\n- [ ] ResponseNotReady sent when crypto operation exceeds timeout threshold\\n- [ ] RDTExponent correctly reflects expected completion time\\n- [ ] RESPOND_IF_READY correctly returns deferred response\\n- [ ] spdm_emu handles ResponseNotReady flow correctly\\n- [ ] Unit tests pass for relevant functionality\\n- [ ] Code reviewed and merged\\n\\n## Confidence: MEDIUM\\n## Complexity: M\",\"components\":[\"firmware\"],\"labels\":[\"feature-planning\",\"confidence-medium\",\"complexity-m\"],\"complexity\":\"M\",\"confidence\":\"medium\",\"acceptance_criteria\":[\"ResponseNotReady sent when crypto operation exceeds timeout threshold\",\"RDTExponent correctly reflects expected completion time\",\"RESPOND_IF_READY correctly returns deferred response\",\"spdm_emu handles ResponseNotReady flow correctly\",\"Unit tests pass for relevant functionality\",\"Code reviewed and merged\"],\"dependencies\":[\"Benchmark CASPER crypto on LPC55S69 eval board\",\"libspdm Responder integration\"],\"assignee\":null},{\"summary\":\"[FW] Error handling & SPDM error responses\",\"description\":\"## Overview\\nImplement comprehensive SPDM error response handling: invalid requests, unsupported commands, unexpected state transitions, truncated packets, wrong algorithms. Return appropriate SPDM ERROR response codes.\\n\\n## Rationale\\nRobust error handling is essential for a production SPDM Responder. Malformed or unexpected requests must be handled gracefully without crashes, buffer overreads, or undefined behavior. This is a security-critical component.\\n\\n## Dependencies\\n- BLOCKED_BY: libspdm Responder integration\\n\\n## Acceptance Criteria\\n- [ ] Invalid SPDM request returns appropriate ERROR response code\\n- [ ] Truncated packets handled without crash or buffer overread\\n- [ ] Wrong algorithm negotiation returns correct error\\n- [ ] Unexpected state transitions handled per SPDM 1.2 spec\\n- [ ] No undefined behavior on any malformed input\\n- [ ] Unit tests pass for relevant functionality\\n- [ ] Code reviewed and merged\\n\\n## Confidence: MEDIUM\\n## Complexity: M\",\"components\":[\"firmware\"],\"labels\":[\"feature-planning\",\"confidence-medium\",\"complexity-m\"],\"complexity\":\"M\",\"confidence\":\"medium\",\"acceptance_criteria\":[\"Invalid SPDM request returns appropriate ERROR response code\",\"Truncated packets handled without crash or buffer overread\",\"Wrong algorithm negotiation returns correct error\",\"Unexpected state transitions handled per SPDM 1.2 spec\",\"No undefined behavior on any malformed input\",\"Unit tests pass for relevant functionality\",\"Code reviewed and merged\"],\"dependencies\":[\"libspdm Responder integration\"],\"assignee\":null},{\"summary\":\"[FW] Real SMBus integration (MCU \u2194 BMC on hardware)\",\"description\":\"## Overview\\nIntegrate and test the full MCTP/SMBus communication path between the NXP MCU and the real BMC on hardware. Verify end-to-end packet delivery over physical SMBus.\\n\\n## Rationale\\nAll preceding transport and protocol stories were developed and tested with loopback or emulated transports. This story validates the complete stack on real hardware with the actual BMC, which is the production deployment target.\\n\\n## Dependencies\\n- BLOCKED_BY: ResponseNotReady mechanism for slow CASPER operations\\n- BLOCKED_BY: Error handling & SPDM error responses\\n- NOTE: The original scope listed a dependency on 'End-to-end loopback test (spdm_emu over TCP proxy)' which was excluded as a test item. The relevant loopback validation criteria (spdm_emu basic flow) are covered in the libspdm Responder integration Story's acceptance criteria.\\n\\n## Acceptance Criteria\\n- [ ] MCTP packets successfully exchanged between MCU and BMC over physical SMBus\\n- [ ] No packet loss or corruption under normal operation\\n- [ ] MCU correctly handles BMC MCTP discovery (Get Endpoint ID)\\n- [ ] SPDM messages correctly transported end-to-end\\n- [ ] Unit tests pass for relevant functionality\\n- [ ] Code reviewed and merged\\n\\n## Open Question: What is the BMC's SPDM Requester implementation and version? This affects interoperability testing.\\n\\n## Confidence: MEDIUM\\n## Complexity: L\",\"components\":[\"firmware\"],\"labels\":[\"feature-planning\",\"confidence-medium\",\"complexity-l\"],\"complexity\":\"L\",\"confidence\":\"medium\",\"acceptance_criteria\":[\"MCTP packets successfully exchanged between MCU and BMC over physical SMBus\",\"No packet loss or corruption under normal operation\",\"MCU correctly handles BMC MCTP discovery (Get Endpoint ID)\",\"SPDM messages correctly transported end-to-end\",\"Unit tests pass for relevant functionality\",\"Code reviewed and merged\"],\"dependencies\":[\"ResponseNotReady mechanism for slow CASPER operations\",\"Error handling & SPDM error responses\"],\"assignee\":null}]},{\"summary\":\"[SPDM] Crypto, Identity & Certificates\",\"description\":\"## Overview\\nThis epic covers the vertical slice from CASPER crypto benchmarking through the complete device identity and certificate chain: crypto backend, PUF key enrollment, CA hierarchy design, certificate slot management, and real Cornelis CA-signed certificate deployment.\\n\\n## Rationale\\nSPDM attestation requires a hardware-rooted device identity (PUF-derived ECC P-256 key) and a valid X.509 certificate chain signed by the Cornelis CA hierarchy. This epic delivers the complete crypto and identity pipeline from hardware acceleration through production certificate deployment.\\n\\n## Scope Items\\n1. Benchmark CASPER crypto on LPC55S69 eval board\\n2. Design Cornelis CA hierarchy & cert templates\\n3. CASPER crypto backend for Mbed TLS\\n4. PUF key enrollment & device key derivation\\n5. Certificate slot management\\n6. Real certificate chain (Cornelis CA-signed)\\n\\n## Open Questions\\n- Which specific LPC55S69 or LPC55S3x variant is being used on the production board?\\n- What is the Cornelis root CA key management and ceremony process?\\n\\n## Assumptions\\n- The CASPER crypto accelerator supports ECC P-256 with sufficient performance for SPDM response times.\\n- PUF key derivation on LPC55S69 is deterministic across power cycles after enrollment.\\n- Only certificate slot 0 is needed (single device identity).\\n- OCP Attestation v1.0 compliance is required for the certificate and measurement format.\",\"components\":[\"firmware\"],\"labels\":[\"feature-planning\"],\"stories\":[{\"summary\":\"[FW] Benchmark CASPER crypto on LPC55S69 eval board\",\"description\":\"## Overview\\nBenchmark CASPER hardware crypto accelerator performance for ECC P-256 sign/verify and SHA-256/SHA-384 operations on the LPC55S69 eval board. Determine if ResponseNotReady is needed for any operations.\\n\\n## Rationale\\nSPDM response times are bounded by the SPDM timeout specification. The CASPER accelerator's actual performance for ECC P-256 sign (the most latency-sensitive operation, used in CHALLENGE and signed GET_MEASUREMENTS) determines whether the ResponseNotReady mechanism is needed. This benchmark must be completed before crypto backend and protocol integration work.\\n\\n## Dependencies\\n- None (root item)\\n\\n## Acceptance Criteria\\n- [ ] ECC P-256 sign latency measured and documented\\n- [ ] ECC P-256 verify latency measured and documented\\n- [ ] SHA-256 and SHA-384 throughput measured for representative firmware image sizes\\n- [ ] Determination made on whether ResponseNotReady is needed for any operation\\n- [ ] Unit tests pass for relevant functionality\\n- [ ] Code reviewed and merged\\n\\n## Confidence: HIGH\\n## Complexity: M\",\"components\":[\"firmware\"],\"labels\":[\"feature-planning\",\"confidence-high\",\"complexity-m\"],\"complexity\":\"M\",\"confidence\":\"high\",\"acceptance_criteria\":[\"ECC P-256 sign latency measured and documented\",\"ECC P-256 verify latency measured and documented\",\"SHA-256 and SHA-384 throughput measured for representative firmware image sizes\",\"Determination made on whether ResponseNotReady is needed for any operation\",\"Unit tests pass for relevant functionality\",\"Code reviewed and merged\"],\"dependencies\":[],\"assignee\":null},{\"summary\":\"[TOOL] Design Cornelis CA hierarchy & cert templates\",\"description\":\"## Overview\\nDesign the X.509 certificate authority hierarchy for Cornelis SPDM attestation: root CA, intermediate CA, device certificate template. Define key usage, validity periods, subject naming, and OCP Attestation v1.0 compliance requirements.\\n\\n## Rationale\\nThe certificate hierarchy is the trust anchor for SPDM attestation. The BMC's SPDM Requester must be able to validate the device certificate chain back to the Cornelis root CA. The design must comply with OCP Attestation v1.0 requirements and be defined before certificate slot management or real certificate deployment can proceed.\\n\\n## Dependencies\\n- None (root item)\\n\\n## Acceptance Criteria\\n- [ ] Root CA, intermediate CA, and device cert template defined\\n- [ ] Key usage extensions specified (digitalSignature for device cert)\\n- [ ] Subject naming convention defined\\n- [ ] Validity periods defined\\n- [ ] OCP Attestation v1.0 certificate requirements met\\n- [ ] Unit tests pass for relevant functionality\\n- [ ] Code reviewed and merged\\n\\n## Open Question: What is the Cornelis root CA key management and ceremony process?\\n\\n## Confidence: MEDIUM\\n## Complexity: M\",\"components\":[\"tools\"],\"labels\":[\"feature-planning\",\"confidence-medium\",\"complexity-m\"],\"complexity\":\"M\",\"confidence\":\"medium\",\"acceptance_criteria\":[\"Root CA, intermediate CA, and device cert template defined\",\"Key usage extensions specified (digitalSignature for device cert)\",\"Subject naming convention defined\",\"Validity periods defined\",\"OCP Attestation v1.0 certificate requirements met\",\"Unit tests pass for relevant functionality\",\"Code reviewed and merged\"],\"dependencies\":[],\"assignee\":null},{\"summary\":\"[FW] CASPER crypto backend for Mbed TLS\",\"description\":\"## Overview\\nImplement a hardware-accelerated crypto backend that routes Mbed TLS ECC P-256 and SHA-256/SHA-384 operations through the LPC55S69 CASPER accelerator. No custom crypto implementations \u2014 use CASPER hardware + Mbed TLS only.\\n\\n## Rationale\\nThe SPDM protocol requires ECC P-256 for signing (CHALLENGE, signed GET_MEASUREMENTS) and SHA-256/SHA-384 for hashing (measurements, certificate digests). Using the CASPER hardware accelerator provides the performance needed to meet SPDM response time requirements while avoiding error-prone custom crypto implementations.\\n\\n## Dependencies\\n- BLOCKED_BY: Benchmark CASPER crypto on LPC55S69 eval board\\n- BLOCKED_BY: MCU project scaffolding (FreeRTOS + NXP SDK + CMake) [in Epic: MCU Platform, Secure Boot & Provisioning]\\n\\n## Acceptance Criteria\\n- [ ] NIST CAVP test vectors pass for ECC P-256 sign and verify\\n- [ ] NIST CAVP test vectors pass for SHA-256 and SHA-384\\n- [ ] All operations use CASPER hardware accelerator (no software fallback)\\n- [ ] Mbed TLS alt function hooks correctly route to CASPER\\n- [ ] Unit tests pass for relevant functionality\\n- [ ] Code reviewed and merged\\n\\n## Confidence: HIGH\\n## Complexity: L\",\"components\":[\"firmware\"],\"labels\":[\"feature-planning\",\"confidence-high\",\"complexity-l\"],\"complexity\":\"L\",\"confidence\":\"high\",\"acceptance_criteria\":[\"NIST CAVP test vectors pass for ECC P-256 sign and verify\",\"NIST CAVP test vectors pass for SHA-256 and SHA-384\",\"All operations use CASPER hardware accelerator (no software fallback)\",\"Mbed TLS alt function hooks correctly route to CASPER\",\"Unit tests pass for relevant functionality\",\"Code reviewed and merged\"],\"dependencies\":[\"Benchmark CASPER crypto on LPC55S69 eval board\",\"MCU project scaffolding (FreeRTOS + NXP SDK + CMake)\"],\"assignee\":null},{\"summary\":\"[FW] PUF key enrollment & device key derivation\",\"description\":\"## Overview\\nImplement PUF (Physical Unclonable Function) key enrollment on the LPC55S69 and derive the ECC P-256 device signing key from PUF. This key is used for SPDM challenge-response signing.\\n\\n## Rationale\\nThe PUF provides a hardware-rooted, device-unique key that cannot be extracted or cloned. The derived ECC P-256 key pair serves as the device identity for SPDM attestation \u2014 the private key signs CHALLENGE responses and the public key is embedded in the device certificate.\\n\\n## Dependencies\\n- BLOCKED_BY: CASPER crypto backend for Mbed TLS\\n\\n## Acceptance Criteria\\n- [ ] PUF enrollment completes successfully\\n- [ ] Key derivation produces the same key deterministically across power cycles\\n- [ ] Derived ECC P-256 key pair is valid (public key on curve, sign/verify round-trip)\\n- [ ] Private key is never exposed in plaintext outside CASPER\\n- [ ] Unit tests pass for relevant functionality\\n- [ ] Code reviewed and merged\\n\\n## Confidence: MEDIUM\\n## Complexity: L\",\"components\":[\"firmware\"],\"labels\":[\"feature-planning\",\"confidence-medium\",\"complexity-l\"],\"complexity\":\"L\",\"confidence\":\"medium\",\"acceptance_criteria\":[\"PUF enrollment completes successfully\",\"Key derivation produces the same key deterministically across power cycles\",\"Derived ECC P-256 key pair is valid (public key on curve, sign/verify round-trip)\",\"Private key is never exposed in plaintext outside CASPER\",\"Unit tests pass for relevant functionality\",\"Code reviewed and merged\"],\"dependencies\":[\"CASPER crypto backend for Mbed TLS\"],\"assignee\":null},{\"summary\":\"[FW] Certificate slot management\",\"description\":\"## Overview\\nImplement certificate slot 0 management: store and serve X.509 certificate chain (device cert \u2192 intermediate CA \u2192 Cornelis root CA) to SPDM Requester via GET_DIGESTS and GET_CERTIFICATE. Single slot only (slot 0).\\n\\n## Rationale\\nThe SPDM Requester uses GET_DIGESTS and GET_CERTIFICATE to retrieve the device's certificate chain for authentication. The certificate slot must correctly store the chain and serve it with proper portion length handling for multi-packet responses.\\n\\n## Dependencies\\n- BLOCKED_BY: Design Cornelis CA hierarchy & cert templates\\n- BLOCKED_BY: PUF key enrollment & device key derivation\\n\\n## Acceptance Criteria\\n- [ ] Certificate chain stored in MCU flash and retrievable\\n- [ ] GET_DIGESTS returns correct hash of certificate chain\\n- [ ] GET_CERTIFICATE returns complete chain with correct portion length handling\\n- [ ] openssl verify validates the returned certificate chain\\n- [ ] Only slot 0 is advertised\\n- [ ] Unit tests pass for relevant functionality\\n- [ ] Code reviewed and merged\\n\\n## Confidence: MEDIUM\\n## Complexity: M\",\"components\":[\"firmware\"],\"labels\":[\"feature-planning\",\"confidence-medium\",\"complexity-m\"],\"complexity\":\"M\",\"confidence\":\"medium\",\"acceptance_criteria\":[\"Certificate chain stored in MCU flash and retrievable\",\"GET_DIGESTS returns correct hash of certificate chain\",\"GET_CERTIFICATE returns complete chain with correct portion length handling\",\"openssl verify validates the returned certificate chain\",\"Only slot 0 is advertised\",\"Unit tests pass for relevant functionality\",\"Code reviewed and merged\"],\"dependencies\":[\"Design Cornelis CA hierarchy & cert templates\",\"PUF key enrollment & device key derivation\"],\"assignee\":null},{\"summary\":\"[FW] Real certificate chain (Cornelis CA-signed)\",\"description\":\"## Overview\\nReplace test certificates with real Cornelis CA-signed certificate chain: device cert \u2192 intermediate CA \u2192 Cornelis root CA. Device cert contains PUF-derived public key.\\n\\n## Rationale\\nDevelopment and testing use self-signed or test certificates. For production deployment, the device certificate must be signed by the Cornelis CA hierarchy so that the BMC's SPDM Requester can validate the chain against the trusted Cornelis root CA.\\n\\n## Dependencies\\n- BLOCKED_BY: Design Cornelis CA hierarchy & cert templates\\n- BLOCKED_BY: Certificate slot management\\n\\n## Acceptance Criteria\\n- [ ] Device certificate signed by Cornelis intermediate CA\\n- [ ] Certificate chain validates with openssl verify\\n- [ ] Device cert public key matches PUF-derived key\\n- [ ] Certificate key usage includes digitalSignature\\n- [ ] BMC accepts the certificate chain\\n- [ ] Unit tests pass for relevant functionality\\n- [ ] Code reviewed and merged\\n\\n## Confidence: MEDIUM\\n## Complexity: M\",\"components\":[\"firmware\"],\"labels\":[\"feature-planning\",\"confidence-medium\",\"complexity-m\"],\"complexity\":\"M\",\"confidence\":\"medium\",\"acceptance_criteria\":[\"Device certificate signed by Cornelis intermediate CA\",\"Certificate chain validates with openssl verify\",\"Device cert public key matches PUF-derived key\",\"Certificate key usage includes digitalSignature\",\"BMC accepts the certificate chain\",\"Unit tests pass for relevant functionality\",\"Code reviewed and merged\"],\"dependencies\":[\"Design Cornelis CA hierarchy & cert templates\",\"Certificate slot management\"],\"assignee\":null}]},{\"summary\":\"[SPDM] MCU Platform, Secure Boot & Provisioning\",\"description\":\"## Overview\\nThis epic covers the MCU platform foundation and secure boot chain: project scaffolding, secure boot enablement, debug lockdown, A/B firmware update, anti-rollback counters, and factory provisioning automation.\\n\\n## Rationale\\nThe MCU platform must be securely bootstrapped before it can serve as a trusted attestation agent. This epic delivers the complete platform security chain from initial project setup through production-ready secure boot, firmware update, and factory provisioning.\\n\\n## Scope Items\\n1. MCU project scaffolding (FreeRTOS + NXP SDK + CMake)\\n2. MCU secure boot (signed images, ROTKH in CMPA)\\n3. Debug lockdown (CMPA/CFPA configuration)\\n4. MCU A/B firmware update mechanism\\n5. Anti-rollback counters (monotonic counter in CFPA)\\n6. Factory provisioning automation (NXP SPSDK)\\n\\n## Open Questions\\n- Which specific LPC55S69 or LPC55S3x variant is being used on the production board?\\n- Is FreeRTOS confirmed as the MCU RTOS, or are alternatives being considered?\\n- What is the MCU firmware update delivery mechanism in Phase 3?\\n\\n## Assumptions\\n- FreeRTOS will be used as the MCU RTOS unless explicitly decided otherwise.\\n- NXP MCUXpresso SDK and SPSDK tools are available and licensed for development.\\n- The arm-none-eabi-gcc toolchain is available for cross-compilation.\\n- Factory provisioning will use NXP SPSDK tooling connected via USB/UART to the MCU.\",\"components\":[\"firmware\"],\"labels\":[\"feature-planning\"],\"stories\":[{\"summary\":\"[FW] MCU project scaffolding (FreeRTOS + NXP SDK + CMake)\",\"description\":\"## Overview\\nSet up the MCU firmware project structure with FreeRTOS, NXP MCUXpresso SDK for LPC55S69, and CMake build system. Include basic main.c, FreeRTOSConfig.h, linker script, and startup code.\\n\\n## Rationale\\nThis is the foundational story that all other firmware stories depend on. The project scaffolding establishes the build system, RTOS configuration, and hardware abstraction layer that every subsequent firmware component builds upon.\\n\\n## Dependencies\\n- BLOCKED_BY: Validate SPI flash tap hardware [in Epic: SPI Flash & Measurement Pipeline]\\n- BLOCKED_BY: Validate SMBus topology & EID allocation [in Epic: Transport & Protocol Integration]\\n- BLOCKED_BY: Benchmark CASPER crypto on LPC55S69 eval board [in Epic: Crypto, Identity & Certificates]\\n\\n## Acceptance Criteria\\n- [ ] Project builds successfully with arm-none-eabi-gcc\\n- [ ] FreeRTOS scheduler starts and runs idle task on target\\n- [ ] CMake build system produces ELF and binary outputs\\n- [ ] Binary size is within LPC55S69 flash constraints\\n- [ ] Unit tests pass for relevant functionality\\n- [ ] Code reviewed and merged\\n\\n## Confidence: HIGH\\n## Complexity: S\",\"components\":[\"firmware\"],\"labels\":[\"feature-planning\",\"confidence-high\",\"complexity-s\"],\"complexity\":\"S\",\"confidence\":\"high\",\"acceptance_criteria\":[\"Project builds successfully with arm-none-eabi-gcc\",\"FreeRTOS scheduler starts and runs idle task on target\",\"CMake build system produces ELF and binary outputs\",\"Binary size is within LPC55S69 flash constraints\",\"Unit tests pass for relevant functionality\",\"Code reviewed and merged\"],\"dependencies\":[\"Validate SPI flash tap hardware\",\"Validate SMBus topology & EID allocation\",\"Benchmark CASPER crypto on LPC55S69 eval board\"],\"assignee\":null},{\"summary\":\"[FW] MCU secure boot (signed images, ROTKH in CMPA)\",\"description\":\"## Overview\\nEnable MCU secure boot chain: configure Root of Trust Key Hash (ROTKH) in CMPA, sign MCU firmware images, verify that only signed images boot and unsigned images are rejected.\\n\\n## Rationale\\nThe MCU serves as the root of trust for SPDM attestation. If the MCU itself can boot unsigned or tampered firmware, the entire attestation chain is compromised. Secure boot ensures that only Cornelis-signed MCU firmware can execute.\\n\\n## Dependencies\\n- BLOCKED_BY: MCU project scaffolding (FreeRTOS + NXP SDK + CMake)\\n\\n## Acceptance Criteria\\n- [ ] ROTKH programmed in CMPA\\n- [ ] Signed MCU firmware image boots successfully\\n- [ ] Unsigned MCU firmware image is rejected at boot\\n- [ ] Tampered (modified) signed image is rejected at boot\\n- [ ] Unit tests pass for relevant functionality\\n- [ ] Code reviewed and merged\\n\\n## Confidence: MEDIUM\\n## Complexity: L\",\"components\":[\"firmware\"],\"labels\":[\"feature-planning\",\"confidence-medium\",\"complexity-l\"],\"complexity\":\"L\",\"confidence\":\"medium\",\"acceptance_criteria\":[\"ROTKH programmed in CMPA\",\"Signed MCU firmware image boots successfully\",\"Unsigned MCU firmware image is rejected at boot\",\"Tampered (modified) signed image is rejected at boot\",\"Unit tests pass for relevant functionality\",\"Code reviewed and merged\"],\"dependencies\":[\"MCU project scaffolding (FreeRTOS + NXP SDK + CMake)\"],\"assignee\":null},{\"summary\":\"[FW] Debug lockdown (CMPA/CFPA configuration)\",\"description\":\"## Overview\\nConfigure CMPA and CFPA to lock down debug interfaces (SWD/JTAG) in production. Ensure debug access is disabled after provisioning to prevent key extraction.\\n\\n## Rationale\\nIf SWD/JTAG debug interfaces remain enabled in production, an attacker could extract the PUF-derived private key or tamper with the MCU firmware, defeating the entire attestation security model. Debug lockdown is an irreversible OTP fuse operation that must be part of the production provisioning flow.\\n\\n## Dependencies\\n- BLOCKED_BY: MCU secure boot (signed images, ROTKH in CMPA)\\n\\n## Acceptance Criteria\\n- [ ] SWD/JTAG access disabled after lockdown\\n- [ ] CMPA/CFPA configuration verified via SPSDK readback\\n- [ ] Debug lockdown survives power cycle\\n- [ ] Lockdown is irreversible (OTP fuse)\\n- [ ] Unit tests pass for relevant functionality\\n- [ ] Code reviewed and merged\\n\\n## Confidence: MEDIUM\\n## Complexity: M\",\"components\":[\"firmware\"],\"labels\":[\"feature-planning\",\"confidence-medium\",\"complexity-m\"],\"complexity\":\"M\",\"confidence\":\"medium\",\"acceptance_criteria\":[\"SWD/JTAG access disabled after lockdown\",\"CMPA/CFPA configuration verified via SPSDK readback\",\"Debug lockdown survives power cycle\",\"Lockdown is irreversible (OTP fuse)\",\"Unit tests pass for relevant functionality\",\"Code reviewed and merged\"],\"dependencies\":[\"MCU secure boot (signed images, ROTKH in CMPA)\"],\"assignee\":null},{\"summary\":\"[FW] MCU A/B firmware update mechanism\",\"description\":\"## Overview\\nImplement A/B (dual-bank) firmware update mechanism for the MCU. Allows MCU firmware to be updated in the field while maintaining a known-good fallback image.\\n\\n## Rationale\\nField firmware updates are essential for security patching and feature delivery. The A/B mechanism ensures that a failed update does not brick the MCU \u2014 the previous known-good image remains bootable as a fallback.\\n\\n## Dependencies\\n- BLOCKED_BY: MCU secure boot (signed images, ROTKH in CMPA)\\n\\n## Acceptance Criteria\\n- [ ] New firmware image written to inactive bank\\n- [ ] Boot switches to new image after validation\\n- [ ] Fallback to previous image if new image fails validation\\n- [ ] Update process does not interrupt ongoing attestation\\n- [ ] Unit tests pass for relevant functionality\\n- [ ] Code reviewed and merged\\n\\n## Open Question: What is the MCU firmware update delivery mechanism in Phase 3?\\n\\n## Confidence: MEDIUM\\n## Complexity: L\",\"components\":[\"firmware\"],\"labels\":[\"feature-planning\",\"confidence-medium\",\"complexity-l\"],\"complexity\":\"L\",\"confidence\":\"medium\",\"acceptance_criteria\":[\"New firmware image written to inactive bank\",\"Boot switches to new image after validation\",\"Fallback to previous image if new image fails validation\",\"Update process does not interrupt ongoing attestation\",\"Unit tests pass for relevant functionality\",\"Code reviewed and merged\"],\"dependencies\":[\"MCU secure boot (signed images, ROTKH in CMPA)\"],\"assignee\":null},{\"summary\":\"[FW] Anti-rollback counters (monotonic counter in CFPA)\",\"description\":\"## Overview\\nImplement anti-rollback protection using monotonic counters in the LPC55S69 CFPA. Prevent booting firmware with a version lower than the current counter value.\\n\\n## Rationale\\nWithout anti-rollback protection, an attacker could downgrade the MCU firmware to a version with known vulnerabilities, bypassing security fixes. Monotonic counters in the CFPA (OTP) ensure that firmware versions can only move forward.\\n\\n## Dependencies\\n- BLOCKED_BY: MCU secure boot (signed images, ROTKH in CMPA)\\n\\n## Acceptance Criteria\\n- [ ] Monotonic counter incremented on firmware update\\n- [ ] Boot rejected for firmware with version below counter value\\n- [ ] Counter value survives power cycle (OTP/CFPA)\\n- [ ] Counter cannot be decremented\\n- [ ] Unit tests pass for relevant functionality\\n- [ ] Code reviewed and merged\\n\\n## Confidence: MEDIUM\\n## Complexity: M\",\"components\":[\"firmware\"],\"labels\":[\"feature-planning\",\"confidence-medium\",\"complexity-m\"],\"complexity\":\"M\",\"confidence\":\"medium\",\"acceptance_criteria\":[\"Monotonic counter incremented on firmware update\",\"Boot rejected for firmware with version below counter value\",\"Counter value survives power cycle (OTP/CFPA)\",\"Counter cannot be decremented\",\"Unit tests pass for relevant functionality\",\"Code reviewed and merged\"],\"dependencies\":[\"MCU secure boot (signed images, ROTKH in CMPA)\"],\"assignee\":null},{\"summary\":\"[TOOL] Factory provisioning automation (NXP SPSDK)\",\"description\":\"## Overview\\nDevelop factory provisioning scripts using NXP SPSDK to automate: PUF enrollment, device key derivation, certificate signing request generation, device certificate injection, CMPA/CFPA programming, secure boot enablement, and debug lockdown. Each unit gets a unique device identity.\\n\\n## Rationale\\nFactory provisioning must be automated to ensure consistency, prevent human error, and scale to production volumes. Each MCU unit must receive a unique PUF-derived identity and be securely configured with signed firmware, locked debug interfaces, and a valid certificate chain.\\n\\n## Dependencies\\n- BLOCKED_BY: PUF key enrollment & device key derivation [in Epic: Crypto, Identity & Certificates]\\n- BLOCKED_BY: MCU secure boot (signed images, ROTKH in CMPA)\\n\\n## Acceptance Criteria\\n- [ ] Provisioning script runs end-to-end without manual intervention\\n- [ ] Each provisioned unit has a unique device identity (unique key pair and certificate)\\n- [ ] PUF enrollment and key derivation automated\\n- [ ] CMPA/CFPA programmed correctly\\n- [ ] Secure boot enabled after provisioning\\n- [ ] Provisioning workflow documented\\n- [ ] Unit tests pass for relevant functionality\\n- [ ] Code reviewed and merged\\n\\n## Confidence: MEDIUM\\n## Complexity: L\",\"components\":[\"tools\"],\"labels\":[\"feature-planning\",\"confidence-medium\",\"complexity-l\"],\"complexity\":\"L\",\"confidence\":\"medium\",\"acceptance_criteria\":[\"Provisioning script runs end-to-end without manual intervention\",\"Each provisioned unit has a unique device identity (unique key pair and certificate)\",\"PUF enrollment and key derivation automated\",\"CMPA/CFPA programmed correctly\",\"Secure boot enabled after provisioning\",\"Provisioning workflow documented\",\"Unit tests pass for relevant functionality\",\"Code reviewed and merged\"],\"dependencies\":[\"PUF key enrollment & device key derivation\",\"MCU secure boot (signed images, ROTKH in CMPA)\"],\"assignee\":null}]}],\"open_questions\":[\"Which specific LPC55S69 or LPC55S3x variant is being used on the production board?\",\"What is the BMC's SPDM Requester implementation and version?\",\"How does the MCU determine the active JKR boot slot?\",\"What is the eFuse key hash measurement source and format?\",\"What is the platform HW version measurement source?\",\"Is FreeRTOS confirmed as the MCU RTOS, or are alternatives being considered?\",\"What is the Cornelis root CA key management and ceremony process?\",\"What is the MCU firmware update delivery mechanism in Phase 3?\",\"What happens if SPI flash tap read conflicts with JKR ASIC SPI access?\",\"The scope item 'Real SMBus integration' depends on 'End-to-end loopback test (spdm_emu over TCP proxy)' which was excluded as a test item. Should this dependency be satisfied by the spdm_emu acceptance criteria on the libspdm Responder integration Story, or does it need separate tracking?\"],\"assumptions\":[\"The NXP LPC55S69 board with SPI flash tap and SMBus connections is available and functional for development.\",\"FreeRTOS will be used as the MCU RTOS unless explicitly decided otherwise.\",\"libspdm v3.8.1 is the SPDM library to be used, with Mbed TLS as the crypto backend.\",\"The BMC has a working SPDM 1.2 Requester implementation available for interop testing.\",\"The SPI flash hardware tap provides reliable read-only access without bus contention issues.\",\"NXP MCUXpresso SDK and SPSDK tools are available and licensed for development.\",\"The arm-none-eabi-gcc toolchain is available for cross-compilation.\",\"SHA-256 is the mandatory measurement hash algorithm; SHA-384 is optional and negotiable.\",\"Only certificate slot 0 is needed (single device identity).\",\"No JKR Xtensa firmware modifications are required or permitted \u2014 MCU operates independently.\",\"The Intel CSS header is included in firmware measurement boundaries for stability.\",\"VPD is treated as a mutable measurement because it is writable via PCIe.\",\"Static MCTP EID allocation is sufficient (no dynamic EID assignment needed).\",\"The MCU does not need to communicate with the JKR ASIC at runtime \u2014 all data is read from SPI flash.\",\"OCP Attestation v1.0 compliance is required for the certificate and measurement format.\",\"Factory provisioning will use NXP SPSDK tooling connected via USB/UART to the MCU.\",\"The CASPER crypto accelerator supports ECC P-256 with sufficient performance for SPDM response times.\",\"PUF key derivation on LPC55S69 is deterministic across power cycles after enrollment.\",\"The JKR SPI flash layout (UEFI, CPORT, Config, VPD addresses) is stable and will not change without notice.\"]}"